# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crystal-structures
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] In crystallography, **atomic packing factor (APF)**, **packing efficiency**, or **packing fraction** is the fraction of volume in a crystal structure that is occupied by constituent particles.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] It is a dimensionless quantity and always less than unity.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] In atomic systems, by convention, the APF is determined by assuming that atoms are rigid spheres.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] The radius of the spheres is taken to be the maximum value such that the atoms do not overlap.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] where *N*particle is the number of particles in the unit cell, *V*particle is the volume of each particle, and *V*unit cell is the volume occupied by the unit cell.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] It can be proven mathematically that for one-component structures, the most dense arrangement of atoms has an APF of about 0.74 (see Kepler conjecture), obtained by the close-packed structures.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] For multiple-component structures (such as with interstitial alloys), the APF can exceed 0.74.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] The atomic packing factor of a unit cell is relevant to the study of materials science, where it explains many properties of materials.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] For example, metals with a high atomic packing factor will have a higher "workability" (malleability or ductility), similar to how a road is smoother when the stones are closer together, allowing metal atoms to slide past one another more easily.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] Common sphere packings taken on by atomic systems are listed below with their corresponding packing fraction.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] The majority of metals take on either the HCP, FCC, or BCC structure.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] For a simple cubic packing, the number of atoms per unit cell is one.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] The side of the unit cell is of length 2*r*, where *r* is the radius of the atom.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] For a face-centered cubic unit cell, the number of atoms is four.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] A line can be drawn from the top corner of a cube diagonally to the bottom corner on the same side of the cube, which is equal to 4*r*.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] The primitive unit cell for the body-centered cubic crystal structure contains several fractions taken from nine atoms (if the particles in the crystal are atoms): one on each corner of the cube and one atom in the center.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] Because the volume of each of the eight corner atoms is shared between eight adjacent cells, each BCC cell contains the equivalent volume of two atoms (one central and one on the corner).
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] Each corner atom touches the center atom.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] A line that is drawn from one corner of the cube through the center and to the other corner passes through 4*r*, where *r* is the radius of an atom.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] By geometry, the length of the diagonal is *a*√3.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] For the hexagonal close-packed structure the derivation is similar.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] Here the unit cell (equivalent to 3 primitive unit cells) is a hexagonal prism containing six atoms (if the particles in the crystal are atoms).
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] Indeed, three are the atoms in the middle layer (inside the prism); in addition, for the top and bottom layers (on the bases of the prism), the central atom is shared with the adjacent cell, and each of the six atoms at the vertices is shared with other six adjacent cells.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] Now let $a\$ be the side length of the base of the prism and $c\$ be its height.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] The latter is twice the distance between adjacent layers, *i. e.*, twice the height of the regular tetrahedron whose vertices are occupied by (say) the central atom of the lower layer, two adjacent non-central atoms of the same layer, and one atom of the middle layer "resting" on the previous three.
[src:crystal-structures/atomic-packing-factor] Obviously, the edge of this tetrahedron is $a\$ .
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] In geometry, **close-packing of equal spheres** is a dense arrangement of congruent spheres in an infinite, regular arrangement (or lattice).
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Carl Friedrich Gauss proved that the highest average density – that is, the greatest fraction of space occupied by spheres – that can be achieved by a lattice packing is ${\textstyle {\frac {\pi }{3{\sqrt {2}}}}\approx 0.74048}$ .
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The same packing density can also be achieved by alternate stackings of the same close-packed planes of spheres, including structures that are aperiodic in the stacking direction.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The Kepler conjecture states that this is the highest density that can be achieved by any arrangement of spheres, either regular or irregular.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] This conjecture was proven by Thomas Hales.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The highest density is so far known only for 1, 2, 3, 8, and 24 dimensions.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Many crystal structures are based on a close-packing of a single kind of atom, or a close-packing of large ions with smaller ions filling the spaces between them.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The cubic and hexagonal arrangements are very close to one another in energy, and it may be difficult to predict which form will be preferred from first principles.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] There are two simple regular lattices that achieve this highest average density.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] They are called **face-centered cubic** (**FCC**) (also called **cubic close packed** (**CCP**) and **hexagonal close-packed** (**HCP**), based on their symmetry.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Both are based upon sheets of spheres arranged at the vertices of a triangular tiling; they differ in how the sheets are stacked upon one another.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The FCC lattice is also known to mathematicians as that generated by the A3 root system.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The problem of close-packing of spheres was first mathematically analyzed by Thomas Harriot around 1587, after a question on piling cannonballs on ships was posed to him by Sir Walter Raleigh on their expedition to America.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Cannonballs were usually piled in a rectangular or triangular wooden frame, forming a three-sided or four-sided pyramid.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Both arrangements produce a face-centered cubic lattice – with different orientation to the ground.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Hexagonal close-packing would result in a six-sided pyramid with a hexagonal base.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] and conjectured that the only solutions are $N=1,M=1,$ and $N=24,M=70$ .
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Here N is the number of layers in the pyramidal stacking arrangement and M is the number of cannonballs along an edge in the flat square arrangement.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] In both the FCC and HCP arrangements each sphere has twelve neighbors.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] For every sphere there is one gap surrounded by six spheres (octahedral) and two smaller gaps surrounded by four spheres (tetrahedral).
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The distances to the centers of these gaps from the centers of the surrounding spheres is √3⁄2 for the tetrahedral, and √2 for the octahedral, when the sphere radius is 1.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Relative to a reference layer with positioning A, two more positionings B and C are possible.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Every sequence of A, B, and C without immediate repetition of the same one is possible and gives an equally dense packing for spheres of a given radius.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] There is an uncountably infinite number of disordered arrangements of planes (e.g.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] ABCACBABABAC...) that are sometimes collectively referred to as "Barlow packings", after crystallographer William Barlow.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] In close-packing, the center-to-center spacing of spheres in the *xy* plane is a simple honeycomb-like tessellation with a pitch (distance between sphere centers) of one sphere diameter.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] where *d* is the diameter of a sphere; this follows from the tetrahedral arrangement of close-packed spheres.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Note how the two balls facing the viewer in the second tier from the top contact the same ball in the tier below.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The difference between this stack and the top three tiers of the cannonball stack all occurs in the bottom tier, which is rotated half the pitch diameter of a sphere (60°).
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Note how the two balls facing the viewer in the second tier from the top do not contact the same ball in the tier below.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] When forming any sphere-packing lattice, the first fact to notice is that whenever two spheres touch a straight line may be drawn from the center of one sphere to the center of the other intersecting the point of contact.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The distance between the centers along the shortest path namely that straight line will therefore be *r*1 + *r*2 where *r*1 is the radius of the first sphere and *r*2 is the radius of the second.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] In close packing all of the spheres share a common radius, *r*.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Therefore, two centers would simply have a distance 2*r*.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] To form an A-B-A-B-... hexagonal close packing of spheres, the coordinate points of the lattice will be the spheres' centers.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Suppose, the goal is to fill a box with spheres according to HCP.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The box would be placed on the *x*-*y*-*z* coordinate space.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The centers will all lie on a straight line.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Their *x*-coordinate will vary by 2*r* since the distance between each center of the spheres are touching is 2*r*.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The *y*-coordinate and z-coordinate will be the same.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] For simplicity, say that the balls are the first row and that their *y*- and *z*-coordinates are simply *r*, so that their surfaces rest on the zero-planes.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Again, the centers will all lie on a straight line with *x*-coordinate differences of 2*r*, but there will be a shift of distance *r* in the *x*-direction so that the center of every sphere in this row aligns with the *x*-coordinate of where two spheres touch in the first row.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] This allows the spheres of the new row to slide in closer to the first row until all spheres in the new row are touching two spheres of the first row.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Since the new spheres *touch* two spheres, their centers form an equilateral triangle with those two neighbors' centers.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The side lengths are all 2*r*, so the height or *y*-coordinate difference between the rows is √3*r*.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The first sphere of this row only touches one sphere in the original row, but its location follows suit with the rest of the row.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The next row follows this pattern of shifting the *x*-coordinate by *r* and the *y*-coordinate by √3.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Add rows until reaching the *x* and *y* maximum borders of the box.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] In an A-B-A-B-... stacking pattern, the odd numbered *planes* of spheres will have exactly the same coordinates save for a pitch difference in the *z*-coordinates and the even numbered *planes* of spheres will share the same *x*- and *y*-coordinates.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Both types of planes are formed using the pattern mentioned above, but the starting place for the *first* row's first sphere will be different.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Using the plane described precisely above as plane #1, the A plane, place a sphere on top of this plane so that it lies touching three spheres in the A-plane.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The three spheres are all already touching each other, forming an equilateral triangle, and since they all touch the new sphere, the four centers form a regular tetrahedron.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] All of the sides are equal to 2*r* because all of the sides are formed by two spheres touching.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The height of which or the *z*-coordinate difference between the two "planes" is ⁠√6*r*2/3⁠.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The difference to the next plane, the A plane, is again 2√2/3r in the *z*-direction and a shift in the *x* and *y* to match those *x*- and *y*-coordinates of the first A plane.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] where i, j, and k are indices starting at 0 for the *x*-, *y*-, and *z*-coordinates.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Crystallographic features of HCP systems, such as vectors and atomic plane families, can be described using a four-value Miller index notation ( *hkil* ) in which the third index *i* denotes a degenerate but convenient component which is equal to −*h* − *k*.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The *h*, *i* and *k* index directions are separated by 120°, and are thus not orthogonal; the *l* component is mutually perpendicular to the *h*, *i* and *k* index directions.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The FCC and HCP packings are the densest known packings of equal spheres with the highest symmetry (smallest repeat units).
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Denser sphere packings are known, but they involve unequal sphere packing.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] A packing density of 1, filling the space completely, requires non-spherical shapes, such as honeycombs.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Replacing each contact point between two spheres with an edge connecting the centers of the touching spheres produces tetrahedrons and octahedrons of equal edge lengths.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The FCC arrangement produces the tetrahedral-octahedral honeycomb.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The HCP arrangement produces the gyrated tetrahedral-octahedral honeycomb.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] If, instead, every sphere is augmented with the points in space that are closer to it than to any other sphere, the duals of these honeycombs are produced: the rhombic dodecahedral honeycomb for FCC, and the trapezo-rhombic dodecahedral honeycomb for HCP.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Spherical bubbles appear in soapy water in a FCC or HCP arrangement when the water in the gaps between the bubbles drains out.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] This pattern also approaches the rhombic dodecahedral honeycomb or trapezo-rhombic dodecahedral honeycomb.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] However, such FCC or HCP foams of very small liquid content are unstable, as they do not satisfy Plateau's laws.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] The Kelvin foam and the Weaire–Phelan foam are more stable, having smaller interfacial energy in the limit of a very small liquid content.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] There are two types of interstitial holes left by hcp and fcc conformations: tetrahedral and octahedral void.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Four spheres surround the tetrahedral hole with three spheres being in one layer and one sphere from the next layer.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Six spheres surround an octahedral voids with three spheres coming from one layer and three spheres coming from the next layer.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Structures of many simple chemical compounds, for instance, are often described in terms of small atoms occupying tetrahedral or octahedral holes in closed-packed systems that are formed from larger atoms.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Layered structures are formed by alternating empty and filled octahedral planes.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] Two octahedral layers usually allow for four structural arrangements that can either be filled by an hpc of fcc packing systems.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] In filling tetrahedral holes a complete filling leads to fcc field array.
[src:crystal-structures/close-packing-of-equal-spheres] In unit cells, hole filling can sometimes lead to polyhedral arrays with a mix of hcp and fcc layering.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] The **coordination geometry** of an atom is the geometrical pattern defined by the atoms around the central atom.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] The term is commonly applied in the field of inorganic chemistry, where diverse structures are observed.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] The coordination geometry depends on the number, not the type, of ligands bonded to the metal centre as well as their locations.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] The number of atoms bonded is the coordination number.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] The geometrical pattern can be described as a polyhedron where the vertices of the polyhedron are the centres of the coordinating atoms in the ligands.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] The coordination preference of a metal often varies with its oxidation state.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] The number of coordination bonds (coordination number) can vary from two in K[Ag(CN)2] as high as 20 in Th(*η*5-C5H5)4.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] One of the most common coordination geometries is octahedral, where six ligands are coordinated to the metal in a symmetrical distribution, leading to the formation of an octahedron if lines were drawn between the ligands.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] Other common coordination geometries are tetrahedral and square planar.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] Crystal field theory may be used to explain the relative stabilities of transition metal compounds of different coordination geometry, as well as the presence or absence of paramagnetism, whereas VSEPR may be used for complexes of main group element to predict geometry.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] In a crystal structure the coordination geometry of an atom is the geometrical pattern of coordinating atoms where the definition of coordinating atoms depends on the bonding model used.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] For example, in the rock salt ionic structure each sodium atom has six near neighbour chloride ions in an octahedral geometry and each chloride has similarly six near neighbour sodium ions in an octahedral geometry.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] In metals with the body centred cubic (bcc) structure each atom has eight nearest neighbours in a cubic geometry.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] In metals with the face centred cubic (fcc) structure each atom has twelve nearest neighbours in a cuboctahedral geometry.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] A table of the coordination geometries encountered is shown below with examples of their occurrence in complexes found as discrete units in compounds and coordination spheres around atoms in crystals (where there is no discrete complex).
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] IUPAC have introduced the polyhedral symbol as part of their IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry 2005 recommendations to describe the geometry around an atom in a compound.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] IUCr have proposed a symbol which is shown as a superscript in square brackets in the chemical formula.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] For example, CaF2 would be Ca[8cb]F2[4t], where [8cb] means cubic coordination and [4t] means tetrahedral.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] The equivalent symbols in IUPAC are *CU*−8 and *T*−4 respectively.
[src:crystal-structures/coordination-geometry] The IUPAC symbol is applicable to complexes and molecules whereas the IUCr proposal applies to crystalline solids.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In crystallography, **crystal structure** is a description of the ordered arrangement of atoms, ions, or molecules in a crystalline material.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Ordered structures occur from the intrinsic nature of constituent particles to form symmetric patterns that repeat along the principal directions of three-dimensional space in matter.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The smallest group of particles in a material that constitutes this repeating pattern is the unit cell of the structure.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The unit cell completely reflects the symmetry and structure of the entire crystal, which is built up by repetitive translation of the unit cell along its principal axes.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The translation vectors define the nodes of the Bravais lattice.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The lengths of principal axes/edges, of the unit cell and angles between them are lattice constants, also called *lattice parameters* or *cell parameters*.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The symmetry properties of a crystal are described by the concept of space groups.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] All possible symmetric arrangements of particles in three-dimensional space may be described by 230 space groups.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The crystal structure and symmetry play a critical role in determining many physical properties, such as cleavage, electronic band structure, and optical transparency.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Crystal structure is described in terms of the geometry of the arrangement of particles in the unit cells.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The unit cell is defined as the smallest repeating unit having the full symmetry of the crystal structure.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The geometry of the unit cell is defined as a parallelepiped, providing six lattice parameters taken as the lengths of the cell edges (*a*, *b*, *c*) and the angles between them (α, β, γ).
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The positions of particles inside the unit cell are described by the fractional coordinates (*xi*, *yi*, *zi*) along the cell edges, measured from a reference point.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] It is thus only necessary to report the coordinates of a smallest asymmetric subset of particles, called the crystallographic asymmetric unit.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The asymmetric unit may be chosen so that it occupies the smallest physical space, which means that not all particles need to be physically located inside the boundaries given by the lattice parameters.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] All other particles of the unit cell are generated by the symmetry operations that characterize the symmetry of the unit cell.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The collection of symmetry operations of the unit cell is expressed formally as the space group of the crystal structure.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Vectors and planes in a crystal lattice are described by the three-value Miller index notation.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] This syntax uses the indices *h*, *k*, and *ℓ* as directional parameters.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] By definition, the syntax (*hkℓ*) denotes a plane that intercepts the three points *a*1/*h*, *a*2/*k*, and *a*3/*ℓ*, or some multiple thereof.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] That is, the Miller indices are proportional to the inverses of the intercepts of the plane with the unit cell (in the basis of the lattice vectors).
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] If one or more of the indices is zero, the planes do not intersect that axis (i.e., the intercept is "at infinity").
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] A plane containing a coordinate axis is translated to no longer contain that axis before its Miller indices are determined.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The Miller indices for a plane are integers with no common factors.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Negative indices are indicated with horizontal bars, as in (123).
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In an orthogonal coordinate system for a cubic cell, the Miller indices of a plane are the Cartesian components of a vector normal to the plane.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The crystallographic directions are geometric lines linking nodes (atoms, ions or molecules) of a crystal.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Likewise, the crystallographic planes are geometric *planes* linking nodes.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Some directions and planes have a higher density of nodes.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Some directions and planes are defined by symmetry of the crystal system.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In monoclinic, trigonal, tetragonal, and hexagonal systems there is one unique axis (sometimes called the **principal axis**) which has higher rotational symmetry than the other two axes.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The **basal plane** is the plane perpendicular to the principal axis in these crystal systems.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] For triclinic, orthorhombic, and cubic crystal systems the axis designation is arbitrary and there is no principal axis.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] For the special case of simple cubic crystals, the lattice vectors are orthogonal and of equal length (usually denoted *a*); similarly for the reciprocal lattice.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] So, in this common case, the Miller indices (*ℓmn*) and [*ℓmn*] both simply denote normals/directions in Cartesian coordinates.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] For face-centered cubic (fcc) and body-centered cubic (bcc) lattices, the primitive lattice vectors are not orthogonal.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] However, in these cases the Miller indices are conventionally defined relative to the lattice vectors of the cubic supercell and hence are again simply the Cartesian directions.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The defining property of a crystal is its inherent symmetry.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Performing certain symmetry operations on the crystal lattice leaves it unchanged.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] All crystals have translational symmetry in three directions, but some have other symmetry elements as well.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] For example, rotating the crystal 180° about a certain axis may result in an atomic configuration that is identical to the original configuration; the crystal has twofold rotational symmetry about this axis.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In addition to rotational symmetry, a crystal may have symmetry in the form of mirror planes, and also the so-called compound symmetries, which are a combination of translation and rotation or mirror symmetries.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] A full classification of a crystal is achieved when all inherent symmetries of the crystal are identified.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Lattice systems are a grouping of crystal structures according to the point groups of their lattice.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] All crystals fall into one of seven lattice systems.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] They are related to, but not the same as the seven crystal systems.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The most symmetric, the cubic or isometric system, has the symmetry of a cube, that is, it exhibits four threefold rotational axes oriented at 109.5° (the tetrahedral angle) with respect to each other.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] These threefold axes lie along the body diagonals of the cube.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The other six lattice systems, are hexagonal, tetragonal, rhombohedral (often confused with the trigonal crystal system), orthorhombic, monoclinic and triclinic which is the least symmetrical as it possess only identity (E).
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Bravais lattices, also referred to as *space lattices*, describe the geometric arrangement of the lattice points, and therefore the translational symmetry of the crystal.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The three dimensions of space afford 14 distinct Bravais lattices describing the translational symmetry.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] All crystalline materials recognized today, not including quasicrystals, fit in one of these arrangements.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The fourteen three-dimensional lattices, classified by lattice system, are shown above.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The crystal structure consists of the same group of atoms, the *basis*, positioned around each and every lattice point.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] This group of atoms therefore repeats indefinitely in three dimensions according to the arrangement of one of the Bravais lattices.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The characteristic rotation and mirror symmetries of the unit cell is described by its crystallographic point group.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Recent developments in crystallography and intermetallic materials science have led to the identification of a new family of ternary compounds known as ZIP phases.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] These structures are characterised by so-called dualistic atomic ordering, in which different atomic sublattices display distinct ordering behaviour within a single crystal lattice.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] A crystal system is a set of point groups in which the point groups themselves and their corresponding space groups are assigned to a lattice system.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Of the 32 point groups that exist in three dimensions, most are assigned to only one lattice system, in which case the crystal system and lattice system both have the same name.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] However, five point groups are assigned to two lattice systems, rhombohedral and hexagonal, because both lattice systems exhibit threefold rotational symmetry.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] These point groups are assigned to the trigonal crystal system.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In total there are seven crystal systems: triclinic, monoclinic, orthorhombic, tetragonal, trigonal, hexagonal, and cubic.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The crystallographic point group or *crystal class* is the mathematical group comprising the symmetry operations that leave at least one point unmoved and that leave the appearance of the crystal structure unchanged.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Rotation axes (proper and improper), reflection planes, and centers of symmetry are collectively called *symmetry elements*.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Each one can be classified into one of the seven crystal systems.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In addition to the operations of the point group, the space group of the crystal structure contains translational symmetry operations.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] By considering the arrangement of atoms relative to each other, their coordination numbers, interatomic distances, types of bonding, etc., it is possible to form a general view of the structures and alternative ways of visualizing them.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The principles involved can be understood by considering the most efficient way of packing together equal-sized spheres and stacking close-packed atomic planes in three dimensions.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] For example, if plane A lies beneath plane B, there are two possible ways of placing an additional atom on top of layer B.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The unit cell of a ccp arrangement of atoms is the face-centered cubic (fcc) unit cell.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] This is not immediately obvious, as the closely packed layers are parallel to the {111} planes of the fcc unit cell.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] There are four different orientations of the close-packed layers.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] One important characteristic of a crystalline structure is its atomic packing factor (APF).
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] This is calculated by assuming that all the atoms are identical spheres, with a radius large enough that each sphere abuts on the next.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Another important characteristic of a crystalline structure is its coordination number (CN).
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] This is the number of nearest neighbours of a central atom in the structure.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The 74% packing efficiency of the FCC and HCP is the maximum density possible in unit cells constructed of spheres of only one size.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Interstitial sites refer to the empty spaces in between the atoms in the crystal lattice.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] These spaces can be filled by oppositely charged ions to form multi-element structures.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] They can also be filled by impurity atoms or self-interstitials to form interstitial defects.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Real crystals feature defects or irregularities in the ideal arrangements described above and it is these defects that critically determine many of the electrical and mechanical properties of real materials.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] When one atom substitutes for one of the principal atomic components within the crystal structure, alteration in the electrical and thermal properties of the material may ensue.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Impurities may also manifest as electron spin impurities in certain materials.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Dislocations in a crystal lattice are line defects that are associated with local stress fields.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Dislocations allow shear at lower stress than that needed for a perfect crystal structure.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The local stress fields result in interactions between the dislocations which then result in strain hardening or cold working.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Grain boundaries are interfaces where crystals of different orientations meet.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] A grain boundary is a single-phase interface, with crystals on each side of the boundary being identical except in orientation.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The term "crystallite boundary" is sometimes, though rarely, used.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Grain boundary areas contain those atoms that have been perturbed from their original lattice sites, dislocations, and impurities that have migrated to the lower energy grain boundary.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Treating a grain boundary geometrically as an interface of a single crystal cut into two parts, one of which is rotated, we see that there are five variables required to define a grain boundary.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The first two numbers come from the unit vector that specifies a rotation axis.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The third number designates the angle of rotation of the grain.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The final two numbers specify the plane of the grain boundary (or a unit vector that is normal to this plane).
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Grain boundaries disrupt the motion of dislocations through a material, so reducing crystallite size is a common way to improve strength, as described by the Hall–Petch relationship.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Since grain boundaries are defects in the crystal structure they tend to decrease the electrical and thermal conductivity of the material.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The high interfacial energy and relatively weak bonding in most grain boundaries often makes them preferred sites for the onset of corrosion and for the precipitation of new phases from the solid.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] They are also important to many of the mechanisms of creep.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Grain boundaries are in general only a few nanometers wide.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In common materials, crystallites are large enough that grain boundaries account for a small fraction of the material.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] However, very small grain sizes are achievable.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In nanocrystalline solids, grain boundaries become a significant volume fraction of the material, with profound effects on such properties as diffusion and plasticity.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In the limit of small crystallites, as the volume fraction of grain boundaries approaches 100%, the material ceases to have any crystalline character, and thus becomes an amorphous solid.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The difficulty of predicting stable crystal structures based on the knowledge of only the chemical composition has long been a stumbling block on the way to fully computational materials design.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Now, with more powerful algorithms and high-performance computing, structures of medium complexity can be predicted using such approaches as evolutionary algorithms, random sampling, or metadynamics.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The crystal structures of simple ionic solids (e.g., NaCl or table salt) have long been rationalized in terms of Pauling's rules, first set out in 1929 by Linus Pauling, referred to by many since as the "father of the chemical bond".
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Pauling also considered the nature of the interatomic forces in metals, and concluded that about half of the five d-orbitals in the transition metals are involved in bonding, with the remaining nonbonding d-orbitals being responsible for the magnetic properties.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Pauling was therefore able to correlate the number of d-orbitals in bond formation with the bond length, as well as with many of the physical properties of the substance.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] He subsequently introduced the metallic orbital, an extra orbital necessary to permit uninhibited resonance of valence bonds among various electronic structures.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In the resonating valence bond theory, the factors that determine the choice of one from among alternative crystal structures of a metal or intermetallic compound revolve around the energy of resonance of bonds among interatomic positions.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] It is clear that some modes of resonance would make larger contributions (be more mechanically stable than others), and that in particular a simple ratio of number of bonds to number of positions would be exceptional.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The resulting principle is that a special stability is associated with the simplest ratios or "bond numbers": 1⁄2, 1⁄3, 2⁄3, 1⁄4, 3⁄4, etc.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The choice of structure and the value of the axial ratio (which determines the relative bond lengths) are thus a result of the effort of an atom to use its valency in the formation of stable bonds with simple fractional bond numbers.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] This treatment thus emphasized the increasing bond strength as a function of group number.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The operation of directional forces were emphasized in one article on the relation between bond hybrids and the metallic structures.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The resulting correlation between electronic and crystalline structures is summarized by a single parameter, the weight of the d-electrons per hybridized metallic orbital.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The "d-weight" calculates out to 0.5, 0.7 and 0.9 for the fcc, hcp and bcc structures respectively.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The relationship between d-electrons and crystal structure thus becomes apparent.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In crystal structure predictions/simulations, the periodicity is usually applied, since the system is imagined as being unlimited in all directions.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Polymorphism is the occurrence of multiple crystalline forms of a material.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] It is found in many crystalline materials including polymers, minerals, and metals.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] According to Gibbs' rules of phase equilibria, these unique crystalline phases are dependent on intensive variables such as pressure and temperature.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Polymorphism is related to allotropy, which refers to elemental solids.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The complete morphology of a material is described by polymorphism and other variables such as crystal habit, amorphous fraction or crystallographic defects.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Polymorphs have different stabilities and may spontaneously and irreversibly transform from a metastable form (or thermodynamically unstable form) to the stable form at a particular temperature.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] They also exhibit different melting points, solubilities, and X-ray diffraction patterns.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] One good example of this is the quartz form of silicon dioxide, or SiO2.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In the vast majority of silicates, the Si atom shows tetrahedral coordination by 4 oxygens.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] All but one of the crystalline forms involve tetrahedral {SiO4} units linked together by shared vertices in different arrangements.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In different minerals the tetrahedra show different degrees of networking and polymerization.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] For example, they occur singly, joined in pairs, in larger finite clusters including rings, in chains, double chains, sheets, and three-dimensional frameworks.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The minerals are classified into groups based on these structures.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] In each of the 7 thermodynamically stable crystalline forms or polymorphs of crystalline quartz, only 2 out of 4 of each the edges of the {SiO4} tetrahedra are shared with others, yielding the net chemical formula for silica: SiO2.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Another example is elemental tin (Sn), which is malleable near ambient temperatures but is brittle when cooled.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] This change in mechanical properties due to existence of its two major allotropes, α- and β-tin.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] The two allotropes that are encountered at normal pressure and temperature, α-tin and β-tin, are more commonly known as *gray tin* and *white tin* respectively.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Two more allotropes, γ and σ, exist at temperatures above 161 °C and pressures above several GPa.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] White tin is metallic, and is the stable crystalline form at or above room temperature.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Below 13.2 °C, tin exists in the gray form, which has a diamond cubic crystal structure, similar to diamond, silicon or germanium.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Gray tin has no metallic properties at all, is a dull gray powdery material, and has few uses, other than a few specialized semiconductor applications.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Although the α–β transformation temperature of tin is nominally 13.2 °C, impurities (e.g.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Al, Zn, etc.) lower the transition temperature well below 0 °C, and upon addition of Sb or Bi the transformation may not occur at all.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Twenty of the 32 crystal classes are piezoelectric, and crystals belonging to one of these classes (point groups) display piezoelectricity.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] All piezoelectric classes lack inversion symmetry.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Any material develops a dielectric polarization when an electric field is applied, but a substance that has such a natural charge separation even in the absence of a field is called a polar material.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Whether or not a material is polar is determined solely by its crystal structure.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Only ten of the 32 point groups are polar.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] All polar crystals are pyroelectric, so the ten polar crystal classes are sometimes referred to as the pyroelectric classes.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] There are a few crystal structures, notably the perovskite structure, which exhibit ferroelectric behavior.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] This is analogous to ferromagnetism, in that, in the absence of an electric field during production, the ferroelectric crystal does not exhibit a polarization.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] Upon the application of an electric field of sufficient magnitude, the crystal becomes permanently polarized.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] This polarization can be reversed by a sufficiently large counter-charge, in the same way that a ferromagnet can be reversed.
[src:crystal-structures/crystal-structure] However, although they are called ferroelectrics, the effect is due to the crystal structure (not the presence of a ferrous metal).
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] In crystallography, the **cubic** (or **isometric**) **crystal system** is a crystal system where the unit cell is in the shape of a cube.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] This is one of the most common and simplest shapes found in crystals and minerals.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Note: the term **fcc** is often used synonymously for the *cubic close-packed* or **ccp** structure occurring in metals.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] However, **fcc** stands for a face-centered cubic Bravais lattice, which is not necessarily close-packed when a motif is set onto the lattice points.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] E.g. the diamond and the zincblende lattices are **fcc** but not close-packed.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Each is subdivided into other variants listed below.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Although the *unit cells* in these crystals are conventionally taken to be cubes, the primitive unit cells often are not.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The primitive cubic lattice (cP) consists of one lattice point on each corner of the cube; this means each simple cubic unit cell has in total one lattice point.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Each atom at a lattice point is then shared equally between eight adjacent cubes, and the unit cell therefore contains in total one atom (1⁄8 × 8).
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The body-centered cubic lattice (cI) has one lattice point in the center of the unit cell in addition to the eight corner points.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] It has a net total of two lattice points per unit cell (1⁄8 × 8 + 1).
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The face-centered cubic lattice (cF) has lattice points on the faces of the cube that each give exactly one half contribution, in addition to the corner lattice points, giving a total of four lattice points per unit cell (1⁄8 × 8 from the corners plus 1⁄2 × 6 from the faces).
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The face-centered cubic lattice is closely related to the hexagonal close packed (hcp) system, where the two systems differ only in the relative placements of their hexagonal layers.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The [111] plane of a face-centered cubic lattice is a hexagonal grid.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Attempting to create a base-centered cubic lattice (i.e., putting an extra lattice point in the center of each horizontal face) results in a simple tetragonal Bravais lattice.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Coordination number (CN) is the number of nearest neighbors of a central atom in the structure.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Each sphere in a cP lattice has coordination number 6, in a cI lattice 8, and in a cF lattice 12.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Atomic packing factor (APF) is the fraction of volume that is occupied by atoms.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The cP lattice has an APF of about 0.524, the cI lattice an APF of about 0.680, and the cF lattice an APF of about 0.740.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The *isometric crystal system* class names, point groups (in Schönflies notation, Hermann–Mauguin notation, orbifold, and Coxeter notation), type, examples, international tables for crystallography space group number, and space groups are listed in the table below.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] There are a total 36 cubic space groups.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Other terms for hexoctahedral are: normal class, holohedral, ditesseral central class, galena type.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] As a rule, since atoms in a solid attract each other, the more tightly packed arrangements of atoms tend to be more common.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] (Loosely packed arrangements do occur, though, for example if the orbital hybridization demands certain bond angles.) Accordingly, the primitive cubic structure, with especially low atomic packing factor, is rare in nature, but is found in polonium.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The *bcc* and *fcc*, with their higher densities, are both quite common in nature.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Examples of *bcc* include iron, chromium, tungsten, and niobium.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Examples of *fcc* include aluminium, copper, gold and silver.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Another important cubic crystal structure is the diamond cubic structure, which can appear in carbon, silicon, germanium, and tin.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Unlike fcc and bcc, this structure is not a lattice, since it contains multiple atoms in its primitive cell.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Other cubic elemental structures include the A15 structure found in tungsten, and the extremely complicated structure of manganese.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Compounds that consist of more than one element (e.g. binary compounds) often have crystal structures based on the cubic crystal system.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Some of the more common ones are listed here.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] These structures can be viewed as two or more interpenetrating sublattices where each sublattice occupies the interstitial sites of the others.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] One structure is the "interpenetrating primitive cubic" structure, also called a "caesium chloride" or B2 structure.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] This structure is often confused for a body-centered cubic structure because the arrangement of atoms is the same.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] However, the caesium chloride structure has a basis composed of two different atomic species.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] In a body-centered cubic structure, there would be translational symmetry along the [111] direction.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] In the caesium chloride structure, translation along the [111] direction results in a change of species.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The structure can also be thought of as two separate simple cubic structures, one of each species, that are superimposed within each other.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The corner of the chloride cube is the center of the caesium cube, and vice versa.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] It works the same way for the NaCl structure described in the next section.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] If you take out the Cl atoms, the leftover Na atoms still form an FCC structure, not a simple cubic structure.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] In the unit cell of CsCl, each ion is at the center of a cube of ions of the opposite kind, so the coordination number is eight.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The central cation is coordinated to 8 anions on the corners of a cube as shown, and similarly, the central anion is coordinated to 8 cations on the corners of a cube.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Alternately, one could view this lattice as a simple cubic structure with a secondary atom in its cubic void.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] In addition to caesium chloride itself, the structure also appears in certain other alkali halides when prepared at low temperatures or high pressures.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Generally, this structure is more likely to be formed from two elements whose ions are of roughly the same size (for example, ionic radius of Cs+ = 167 pm, and Cl− = 181 pm).
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The space group of the caesium chloride (CsCl) structure is called Pm3m (in Hermann–Mauguin notation), or "221" (in the International Tables for Crystallography).
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The Strukturbericht designation is "B2".
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] There are nearly a hundred rare earth intermetallic compounds that crystallize in the CsCl structure, including many binary compounds of rare earths with magnesium, and with elements in groups 11, 12, and 13.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Other compounds showing caesium chloride like structure are CsBr, CsI, high-temperature RbCl, AlCo, AgZn, BeCu, MgCe, RuAl and SrTl.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The space group of the rock-salt or halite (sodium chloride) structure is denoted as Fm3m (in Hermann–Mauguin notation), or "225" (in the International Tables for Crystallography).
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The Strukturbericht designation is "B1".
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] In the rock-salt structure, each of the two atom types forms a separate face-centered cubic lattice, with the two lattices interpenetrating so as to form a 3D checkerboard pattern.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The rock-salt structure has octahedral coordination: Each atom's nearest neighbors consist of six atoms of the opposite type, positioned like the six vertices of a regular octahedron.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] In sodium chloride there is a 1:1 ratio of sodium to chlorine atoms.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The structure can also be described as an FCC lattice of sodium with chlorine occupying each octahedral void or vice versa.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Examples of compounds with this structure include sodium chloride itself, along with almost all other alkali halides, and "many divalent metal oxides, sulfides, selenides, and tellurides".
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] According to the radius ratio rule, this structure is more likely to be formed if the cation is somewhat smaller than the anion (a cation/anion radius ratio of 0.414 to 0.732).
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The interatomic distance (distance between cation and anion, or half the unit cell length *a*) in some rock-salt-structure crystals are: 2.3 Å (2.3 × 10−10 m) for NaF, 2.8 Å for NaCl, and 3.2 Å for SnTe.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Most of the alkali metal hydrides and halides have the rock salt structure, though a few have the caesium chloride structure instead.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Many transition metal monoxides also have the rock salt structure (TiO, VO, CrO, MnO, FeO, CoO, NiO, CdO).
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The early actinoid monocarbides also have this structure (ThC, PaC, UC, NpC, PuC).
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Much like the rock salt structure, the fluorite structure (AB2) is also an Fm3m structure but has 1:2 ratio of ions.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The anti-fluorite structure is nearly identical, except the positions of the anions and cations are switched in the structure.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] They are designated Wyckoff positions 4a and 8c whereas the rock-salt structure positions are 4a and 4b.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The space group of the Zincblende structure is called F43m (in Hermann–Mauguin notation), or 216.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The Strukturbericht designation is "B3".
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The Zincblende structure (also written "zinc blende") is named after the mineral zincblende (sphalerite), one form of zinc sulfide (β-ZnS).
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] As in the rock-salt structure, the two atom types form two interpenetrating face-centered cubic lattices.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] However, it differs from rock-salt structure in how the two lattices are positioned relative to one another.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The zincblende structure has tetrahedral coordination: Each atom's nearest neighbors consist of four atoms of the opposite type, positioned like the four vertices of a regular tetrahedron.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] In zinc sulfide the ratio of zinc to sulfur is 1:1.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Altogether, the arrangement of atoms in zincblende structure is the same as diamond cubic structure, but with alternating types of atoms at the different lattice sites.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The structure can also be described as an FCC lattice of zinc with sulfur atoms occupying half of the tetrahedral voids or vice versa.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Examples of compounds with this structure include zincblende itself, lead(II) nitrate, many compound semiconductors (such as gallium arsenide and cadmium telluride), and a wide array of other binary compounds.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The boron group pnictogenides usually have a zincblende structure, though the nitrides are more common in the wurtzite structure, and their zincblende forms are less well known polymorphs.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] This group is also known as the II-VI family of compounds, most of which can be made in both the zincblende (cubic) or wurtzite (hexagonal) form.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] This group is also known as the **III-V** family of compounds.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The Heusler structure, based on the structure of Cu2MnAl, is a common structure for ternary compounds involving transition metals.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] 225), and the Strukturbericht designation is L21.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Together with the closely related half-Heusler and inverse-Huesler compounds, there are hundreds of examples.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] The space group of the iron monosilicide structure is P213 (No.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] 198), and the Strukturbericht designation is B20.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] This is a chiral structure, and is sometimes associated with helimagnetic properties.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] There are four atoms of each element for a total of eight atoms in the unit cell.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Examples occur among the transition metal silicides and germanides, as well as a few other compounds such as gallium palladide.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] A Weaire–Phelan structure has Pm3n (223) symmetry.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] It has three orientations of stacked tetradecahedrons with pyritohedral cells in the gaps.
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] It is found as a crystal structure in chemistry where it is usually known as a "type I clathrate structure".
[src:crystal-structures/cubic-crystal-system] Gas hydrates formed by methane, propane, and carbon dioxide at low temperatures have a structure in which water molecules lie at the nodes of the Weaire–Phelan structure and are hydrogen bonded together, and the larger gas molecules are trapped in the polyhedral cages.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] In materials science, an **interstitial defect** is a type of point crystallographic defect where an atom of the same or of a different type, occupies an interstitial site in the crystal structure.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] When the atom is of the same type as those already present they are known as a **self-interstitial defect**.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] Alternatively, small atoms in some crystals may occupy interstitial sites, such as hydrogen in palladium.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] Interstitials can be produced by bombarding a crystal with elementary particles having energy above the displacement threshold for that crystal, but they may also exist in small concentrations in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] The presence of interstitial defects can modify the physical and chemical properties of a material.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] The idea of interstitial compounds was started in the late 1930s and they are often called Hagg phases after Gunnar Hägg.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] Transition metals generally crystallise in either the hexagonal close packed or face centered cubic structures, both of which can be considered to be made up of layers of hexagonally close packed atoms.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] These were not viewed as compounds, but rather as solutions, of say carbon, in the metal lattice, with a limiting upper "concentration" of the smaller atom that was determined by the number of interstices available.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] One example is the solubility of carbon in iron.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] The form of pure iron stable between 910 °C and 1390 °C, γ-iron, forms a solid solution with carbon termed austenite which is also known as steel.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] Self-interstitial defects are interstitial defects which contain only atoms which are the same as those already present in the lattice.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] The structure of interstitial defects has been experimentally determined in some metals and semiconductors.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] Contrary to what one might intuitively expect, most self-interstitials in metals with a known structure have a 'split' structure, in which two atoms share the same lattice site.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] Typically the center of mass of the two atoms is at the lattice site, and they are displaced symmetrically from it along one of the principal lattice directions.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] For instance, in several common face-centered cubic (fcc) metals such as copper, nickel and platinum, the ground state structure of the self-interstitial is the split [100] interstitial structure, where two atoms are displaced in a positive and negative [100] direction from the lattice site.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] In body-centered cubic (bcc) iron the ground state interstitial structure is similarly a [110] split interstitial.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] These split interstitials are often called dumbbell interstitials, because plotting the two atoms forming the interstitial with two large spheres and a thick line joining them makes the structure resemble a dumbbell weight-lifting device.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] In semiconductors the situation is more complex, since defects may be charged and different charge states may have different structures.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] For instance, in silicon, the interstitial may either have a split [110] structure or a tetrahedral truly interstitial one.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] Small impurity interstitial atoms are usually on true interstitial sites between the lattice atoms.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] Large impurity interstitials can also be in split interstitial configurations together with a lattice atom, similar to those of the self-interstitial atom.
[src:crystal-structures/interstitial-defect] Interstitials modify the physical and chemical properties of materials.
